answers.body_markdown:
you can define the return type of method `A()` on interface `C` to `number | string,` it has to be a compatible return type.

  

    interface C {
      methodA(): number | string
    }
    
    class A {
      methodA(): string {
        return &#39;42&#39;
      }
    }
    
    class B extends A implements C {
      methodA(): string {
        return super.methodA();
      }
    }

EDIT: so considering your scenario below, it might not be the best solution but you could use the utility type [Omit][1] and create a new type from `C` to avoid the validation of `method1` (more examples [here][2])

    interface C {
      methodA(): number
      //methodB(): string,
      //methodC(): number
      //..
    }
    type C1 = Omit&lt;C, &quot;methodA&quot;&gt;;
    
    class A {
      methodA(): string {
        return &#39;42&#39;
      }
    }
    
    class B extends A implements C1 {
      methodA(): string {
        return super.methodA();
      }
    }

  [1]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/utility-types.html#omittk
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/48215950/exclude-property-from-type

You may make the methodA in class A return type any instead of string.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    interface C {
       methodA(): number
    }

    class A {
      protected methodA(): any {
        return &#39;42&#39;
      }
    }

    class B extends A  implements C {
        methodA(): number {
          return Number(super.methodA());
      }
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

